04698nam a22006615i 9780226439334DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20172017ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2016032946  a9780226439334  a(DE-B1597)524628  a(OCoLC)979417588  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aJA79b.R458 2017 4aJA79b.R458 2017eb 7aPOL0000002bisacsh04a1722231 aRemer, Gary A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEthics and the Orator :bThe Ciceronian Tradition of Political Morality /cGary A. Remer. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (304 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPrologue: Quintilian and John of Salisbury in the Ciceronian Tradition -- t1. Rhetoric, Emotional Manipulation, and Morality: The Contemporary Relevance of Cicero vis-à- vis Aristotle -- t2. Political Morality, Conventional Morality, and Decorum in Cicero -- t3. Rhetoric as a Balancing of Ends: Cicero and Machiavelli -- t4. Justus Lipsius, Morally Acceptable Deceit, and Prudence in the Ciceronian Tradition -- t5. The Classical Orator as Political Representative: Cicero and the Modern Concept of Representation -- t6. Deliberative Democracy and Rhetoric: Cicero, Oratory, and Conversation -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFor thousands of years, critics have attacked rhetoric and the actual practice of politics as unprincipled, insincere, and manipulative. In Ethics and the Orator, Gary A. Remer disagrees, offering the Ciceronian rhetorical tradition as a rejoinder. He argues that the Ciceronian tradition is based on practical or “rhetorical” politics, rather than on idealistic visions of a politics-that-never-was—a response that is ethically sound, if not altogether morally pure. Remer’s study is distinct from other works on political morality in that it turns to Cicero, not Aristotle, as the progenitor of an ethical rhetorical perspective. Contrary to many, if not most, studies of Cicero since the mid-nineteenth century, which have either attacked him as morally indifferent or have only taken his persuasive ends seriously (setting his moral concerns to the side), Ethics and the Orator demonstrates how Cicero presents his ideal orator as exemplary not only in his ability to persuade, but in his capacity as an ethical person. Remer makes a compelling case that Ciceronian values—balancing the moral and the useful, prudential reasoning, and decorum—are not particular only to the philosopher himself, but are distinctive of a broader Ciceronian rhetorical tradition that runs through the history of Western political thought post-Cicero, including the writings of Quintilian, John of Salisbury, Justus Lipsius, Edmund Burke, the authors of The Federalist, and John Stuart Mill.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCicero, Marcus Tullius - Influence. 0aPolitical ethics. 0aPolitical sciencexPhilosophy. 0aRhetoricxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aRhetoricxPolitical aspects. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aCicero.  adecorum.  aethics.  aorator.  apolitical morality.  aprudence.  arhetoric.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDTL Humanities 2020z978311073776908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z97831107119360 cprintz978022643916740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226439334423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226439334/original  a978-3-11-071193-6  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  a978-3-11-073776-9  DTL Hum